        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>29<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</date>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I will go &amp; get the best twisted stems which I can find &amp; will despatch them by this post—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                    <p>Reflecting over what I wrote about movements due to a Pulvinus &amp; to mere circumnutation, I believe that I quite missed the true point.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I think a pulvinus acts by secreting water from its cells into the inter-cellular spaces, so that we ought to get evidence (by comparing transverse sections) of cells on the concave side of petiole of leaf when asleep (which has <hi rend="underline">no</hi> pulvinus) being reduced in size, compared with their size when awake.—</p>
<p>C. D.</p>
<p>Sent by today’s post—</p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>The twisters are</p>
<p>Black Bryony (Tamus)</p>
<p>Azorean Honeysuckle</p>
<p>Common Do—</p>
    <p>Aristolochia Cipho<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p> </figure> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
